### 4. Features
Use a clean list. No nested bullets. No bold everywhere.
Cover:
- Primary key aware diffing
- Cell-level change highlighting
- Side by side view with synced scroll
- IntelliJ-style navigation (F7 / Shift+F7)
- Drag and drop file loading
- Export diff as JSON or CSV
- Files never leave your browser (WebAssembly)
- Works on files up to 200MB
- Free and open source (Apache 2.0)
- Desktop app available (Tauri)

### 5. Try It
Single line:
👉 diffgraft.io

### 6. How It Works
Three steps, plain English:
1. Open two CSV files (drag and drop or click to open)
2. Set your primary key column (auto-detected)
3. See exactly what changed — added, deleted, modified rows

### 7. Why Primary Key Matching Matters
Short section, 3-4 sentences.
Explain the problem: re-sorted files show false differences
without primary key matching.
Example: 10,000 row CSV sorted Z-A instead of A-Z
shows 9,847 false changes with naive text diff.
With primary key matching: zero false changes.

### 8. Tech Stack
Clean table:

| Layer | Technology |
|-------|------------|
| Diff engine | Rust |
| Browser runtime | WebAssembly (wasm-bindgen) |
| Desktop app | Tauri v2 |
| Frontend | React + TypeScript |
| Build tool | Vite |
| Deployment | Cloudflare Pages |

### 9. Running Locally

#### Prerequisites
- Rust (latest stable)
- Node.js v18+
- wasm-pack

#### Desktop app
\`\`\`bash
git clone https://github.com/cyantree-git/diffgraft
cd diffgraft/apps/desktop
npm install
npm run tauri dev
\`\`\`

#### Web app
\`\`\`bash
cd apps/web
npm install
npm run build:wasm
npm run dev
\`\`\`
Open http://localhost:3001

